	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65021161"><p><div class="quote"><p>An opinion about another person is not any type of "news" fake or otherwise.  When an incorrect fact is posted, one would assume that a citation from a well regarded source that disproves that fact would serve as proof of "fake news."</p></div><p>I think the burden of proof is with the party <i>making</i> the claim, not the party refuting it.</p><p>I'm not sure how the Spanish lawmakers intended for this law to work. I'll speculate that someone can challenge something, and the news outlet needs to defend their claim if they can, or withdraw it if they can't. How that differs from libel proceedings in a court, I'll leave for discussion. Someone here already mentioned that the latter is more expensive, so there's that.</p></div>
	</div>

